                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The difference between cleric healing ability and druid healing ability is friggin' huge. Supernal Remedy owns any fast heal druids have. Complete Heal owns every heal the druid has. And clerics can buff HP much better own their own than druids can. PLUS, they've gotten lots of utility added in ways that doesn't overlap with druids. Rez, as you mentioned, plus decent melee (their Time+ procs are really nice), plus the Blessing of Reverence buff line on top of that. Plus, they can take a beating a hell of a lot better than druids. Plus, they have Divine Arbitration, Divine Intervention, the group heal over time, Innate Death Pact...Jeebus Christ, I can go on and on. Clerics have a LOT going for them. "Only advantage the cleric has is rez" is just wrong.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Erm. I hate to make you feel worse or something, but bards can charm too. and snare. and "cast" on the run. Hot dang, I'm gonna make me a bard !</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I don't count bard charm. It's one of their abilities that is actually correctly balanced - maybe a little too weak, even. It costs mana, it doesn't last long, and it's got a weak, weak level cap. I already mentioned the snare. Didn't bring casting on the run into the equation - I guess you can add that to their list of defensive abilities they have that we don't. Oh, yeah, and I thought I made it pretty clear that I don't want to make me a bard. As I said, I like my enchanter.
<br />

<br />
We don't haste better. The bard haste is just as fast (it caps anyone with a good haste item), they can stack an overhaste on top of it, AND it adds a damage shield (one of those druid advantages Arcady was touting that bards have stolen and can do better).
<br />

<br />
We don't mez better, either. If I get a resist, the cleric expends a LOT of mana keeping me alive through something beating the shit out of me in KT, and I spend some mana to refresh my Arcane Rune. If a bard gets a resist, he takes either zero damage (because the mez wasn't enough to get agro), or his damage is significantly mitigated due to the fact that he's in a tin can. We USED to mez better, no doubt about that. I could do things in Seb with AE mez and color shift/slant/skew that Bards would drool over. But the further you get in the endgame, the more and more there are single pulls, and the worse and worse enchanters look as mezzers relative to bards.
<br />

<br />
All the buffs you can provide, a bard can do better. You can do NDT? That's cute, but the bard can DS, haste, overhaste, outmanaregen, increase nuking, and do several other things to boot. You think you can pull? The bards in our guild pull nameds in KodTaz to anywhere in the zone, from anywhere in the zone. They pull Ikkinz trials better than any monk or SK - classes that are DESIGNED for pulling. The only time they stop is when they're very unlucky with Fading Memories and eat a death, and for some reason none of our clerics have Divine Rez up.
<br />

<br />
Sure, in an LDoN normal or hard, I can pull. I can even do it pretty well. But a bard can do it better, faster, and with less deaths.
<br />

<br />
I like the high DPS pet, duh. But that's not applicable everywhere, and the more I play the less I go to places where I can charm. Last I checked, bards don't lose any of their core abilities in endgame zones...ah, wait, that's because they don't have any core abilities, just stuff they've pirated from others. =P
<br />

<br />
And there's something to be said for persistent spells. But not as much as there is to be said for having nearly every ability that classes are balanced around.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
